Comment: I had noticed that my opponent was fond of playing Colle/CZ types of setups. They can be quite powerful if White is able to carry out his plan of development, so it was in Black's best interest to disturb the game immediately.

A simple development move - giving my opponent the chance to play a traditionally proper opening with c4, but with an insidious plan against e3.

An immediate attempt the disturb the development scheme. If 4.dxc5 then 4... Bxd5 and Black has a great position.
White continues with his development plan, where Black typically has a choice between d5 or b6.

Undermining the center and intended development scheme - White will no longer be in familiar waters while Black will have an easy scheme of development. The plan will revolve around Be7, O-O, a queenside fianchetto, knight on either c6/d7 and fighting up the semi-open c-file.
